title: Warm preconditioning protects against acute heat-induced respiratory dysfunction and delays bleaching in a symbiotic sea anemone
site: Key Largo, Florida
trt_no: 3 temp x 17 timepoints = 51
note: Because of a malfunction in the heating apparatus approximately 4 weeks into the preconditioning period, the temperature of the preconditioned treatment briefly (<2h) exceeded 33C (not included in Mock Temp profile). At least another 4 weeks passed before these anemones were heated further, so authors are confident that this brief period of heating did not compromise their subsequent thermal responses.

trt_no: 2 seasons x 2 species x 2 temp treatments x 6 timepoints + 1 timepoint for one season-temp combination for both species (1x2 = 2) + 2 timepoints for one season-temp combination for both species (2x2 = 4) + a time zero timepoint for each season-species combination (1x4 = 4) = 48 + 2 + 4 + 4 = 58
note: Depth: 4-6m. Mocked temperature using Figure S2 and description in Methods and dates in raw data file. Timezero observations: Before fragments were moved into experimental aquaria from the raceway tank. Day1 observations: After moving into the experimental aquaria and aclcimitization, but heating has not begun.

title: Stress-resistant corals may not acclimatize to ocean warming but maintain heat tolerance under cooler temperature
site: Shell Island (Shenton Bluff), Cygnet Bay, NW Australia
trt_no: (12 temperature treatments x 27 timepoints) - 3 timepoints were not measured in 4 temp treatments = 324 - 12 = 312; See Notes
fvfm_name: Maximum quantum yield of photosystem II
note: Fv/Fm was not measured at month 6.25, month 6.5 and month 6.75 for LC_Amb, LC_heat, LV_Amb, and LC_Heat; corals were collected in April 2016 and fragmented in July 2016, acclimation time ~3 months (~ 90 days); Fv/Fm measured time 18:00 - 21:00. I grabbed temperature until 21:00 of the last day of the month or the week for each time series. Control temp for each treatment is the average temperature of the CC_Amb for the same timepoint given in Supplementary Table 2

fvfm_name: Maximum quantum yield of photosystem II
note: Temperatures in the HC and HV treatments were lowered by 2 degree Celsius on Feb 3 2017 (after Month 6) to facilitate recovery and maintained at native - 1 degree Celcius until start of heat stress test.; March 21-23 only has tmeperature from one replicate tank of HC treatment. Fv/Fm was not measured at month 6.25, month 6.5 and month 6.75 for LC_Amb, LC_heat, LV_Amb, and LC_Heat; corals were collected in April 2016 and fragmented in July 2016, acclimation time ~3 months (~ 90 days); Fv/Fm measured time 18:00 - 21:00. I grabbed temperature until 21:00 of the last day of the month or the week for each time series. Control temp for each treatment is the average temperature of the CC_Amb for the same timepoint given in Supplementary Table 2

fvfm_name: Maximum quantum yield of photosystem II
note: 1 coral died Feb 2017; 5 ambient 5 heat stress. Temperatures in the HC and HV treatments were lowered by 2 degree Celsius on Feb 3 2017 (after Month 6) to facilitate recovery and maintained at native - 1 degree Celcius until start of heat stress test.; March 21-23 only has tmeperature from one replicate tank of HC treatment. Fv/Fm was not measured at month 6.25, month 6.5 and month 6.75 for LC_Amb, LC_heat, LV_Amb, and LC_Heat; corals were collected in April 2016 and fragmented in July 2016, acclimation time ~3 months (~ 90 days); Fv/Fm measured time 18:00 - 21:00. I grabbed temperature until 21:00 of the last day of the month or the week for each time series. Control temp for each treatment is the average temperature of the CC_Amb for the same timepoint given in Supplementary Table 2

trt_no: (12 temperature treatments x 27 timepoints) - 3 timepoints were not measured in 4 temp treatments = 324 - 12 = 312; See Notes
fvfm_name: Maximum quantum yield of photosystem II
note: Ramp up started Apr 18, so after Apr 18, corals are maintained at ambient temperature. From Apr 18 to test day 1 May 17 = 29 days =696h observation delay; No temp data Apr 24 23:55 and May 12 9:55 - 10:40. Fv/Fm was not measured at month 6.25, month 6.5 and month 6.75 for LC_Amb, LC_heat, LV_Amb, and LC_Heat; corals were collected in April 2016 and fragmented in July 2016, acclimation time ~3 months (~ 90 days); Fv/Fm measured time 18:00 - 21:00. I grabbed temperature until 21:00 of the last day of the month or the week for each time series. Control temp for each treatment is the average temperature of the CC_Amb for the same timepoint given in Supplementary Table 2

title: Heat attenuation and nutrient delivery by localized upwelling avoided coral bleaching mortality in northern Galapagos during 2015/2016 ENSO
site: Wolf Island, Galapagos archipelago
exp_iv: Site, Species, Health, Tissue of Interest
trt_no: 8: Site 1: 2 species. 1 species has 2 health x 2 tissues of interest (4). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1). 4 + 1 = 5. Site 2: 2 species. 1 species has 1 health x 2 tissues of interest (2). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1) = 3. 5 + 3 = 8
note: Temperature sensors were deployed at Wolf (10m, 15 m, and 20 m) and Darwin (12 m). However, author only sent temp data for Wolf 15m. Was not able to find other temp data. Last timepoint is 2016-03-19 13:47. Use temp at that time as observation temp.

trt_no: 8: Site 1: 2 species. 1 species has 2 health x 2 tissues of interest (4). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1). 4 + 1 = 5. Site 2: 2 species. 1 species has 1 health x 2 tissues of interest (2). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1) = 3. 5 + 3 = 8
note: Temperature sensors were deployed at Wolf (10m, 15 m, and 20 m) and Darwin (12 m). However, author only sent temp data for Wolf 15m. Was not able to find other temp data. Last timepoint is 2016-03-19 13:47. Use temp at that time as observation temp.

title: Heat attenuation and nutrient delivery by localized upwelling avoided coral bleaching mortality in northern Galapagos during 2015/2016 ENSO
site: Wolf Island, Galapagos archipelago
exp_iv: Site, Species, Health, Tissue of Interest
trt_no: 8: Site 1: 2 species. 1 species has 2 health x 2 tissues of interest (4). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1). 4 + 1 = 5. Site 2: 2 species. 1 species has 1 health x 2 tissues of interest (2). 1 species has 1 health x 1 tissues (1) = 3. 5 + 3 = 8
note: In the bleached sections of the partially bleached Porites lobata, tissue showing the normal dark brown color of zooxanthellae-containing cells was observed about 0.4 cm below the skeleton surface. Fv/Fm was measured on the deeper, normally colored tissue layer (coded as ‘‘inside’’) as well as on the bleached surface (coded as ‘‘outside’’). Temperature sensors were deployed at Wolf (10m, 15 m, and 20 m) and Darwin (12 m). However, author only sent temp data for Wolf 15m. Was not able to find other temp data. Last timepoint is 2016-03-19 13:47. Use temp at that time as observation temp.

title: Coral-dwelling fish moderate bleaching susceptibility of coral hosts
site: Lizard Island lagoon
exp_iv: T, Fish, M, Bleaching Conditions, Site
trt_no: Lab: 2 temp x 2 fish x 28 timepoints = 112. Field: Non-Bleaching: Fish and No fish = 2 Bleaching: 4 sites x 2 fish = 8 -> 112+2+8 = 122
note: Depth 0-4m. Ambient temp was 23.5-25 depending on time of day. So I use the average 24.25 as the control temp.

title: Exploring mechanisms that affect coral cooperation: symbiont transmission mode, cell density and community composition
site: Pelorus Island, Great Barrier Reef
trt_no: 6 Species x 2 temp x 3 timepoints = 36
note: Depth <10m. Symbiont density was normalized to both surface area and host protein content. Authors chose to report the data normzlied to protein due to difference in host biomass (tissue thickness is significantly greater in Goniopora columna). However, raw data with symb density normalized to surface area was still available. The 6 coral species are 3 pairs of closely related species of differeing symbiont transmission strategies (vertical or horizontal) : (1)Galaxea acrhelia (VT) and Galaxea astreata (HT); (2) Porites lobata (VT) and Goniopora columna (HT); (3) Montipora aequituberculata (VT) and Acropora millepora (HT).

title: High-frequency temperature variability mirrors fixed differences in thermal limits of the massive coral Porites lobata
site: Ofu and Olosega Islands, territory of American Samoa
trt_no: 3 origins x 2 temp x 5 timepoints = 30
note: 35 days acclimation (stable vs variable) and 5 days of heat stress. For the 5 day heat stress period: All fragments are placed into the variable aquaria. Owing to equipment malfunction, there were two days of the acclimation when the stable aquarium and variable aquarium reached the same high temperature and three days where the stable aquarium reached temperatures below that of the variable aquarium.

title: Effects of temperature and UVR on organic matter fluxes and the metabolic activity of Acropora muricata

site: Reef of ‘phare Amédée’ in the New Caledonian lagoon
trt_no: 2 temp x 2 light = 4
note: Depth: 2-3m. Measurements are taken after 16 days and 28 days of stress. But it was not specified in the raw data which values were from which timepoint, so I only grouped the respvar by treatment (light and temp) but not by timepoint). Mock temp for 28 days using description in Methods.

title: Effects of temperature and UVR on organic matter fluxes and the metabolic activity of Acropora muricata
country: New Caledonia, special collectivity of France
site: Reef of ‘phare Amédée’ in the New Caledonian lagoon

note: Assume measurement was taken at the end (28 days). 28 + 30 days acclimation (where 0UV condition started) = 58 days stressor duration. Depth: 2-3m. Mock temp for 28 days using description in Methods.

title: Energy reserves and metabolism as indicators of coral recovery from bleaching
site: Kaneohe Bay, Coconut Island, Hawaii, USA
trt_no: 2 species x 2 temp x 4 timepoints = 16
sa_method: P. compressa: calculated from branch tips using a cork borer of known area. M. capitata: calculated for a cone or cylinder depending on shape of the branch tips
note: This is the same experiment as S0128. I used the same mock temp profile. Symbiont density and chl a are both normalized to ash-free dry weight, I calculated chl a p cell from those values.

title: Relationships among thermal stress, bleaching and oxidative damage in the hermatypic coral, Pocillopora capitata
site: Bay of Santiago, Manzanillo, México
trt_no: 1 temp x 3 conditions x 6 timepoints = 18
sa_method: Assume the coral to have a cylindrical shape. Formula: A= 2?rh+ 2?r 2
ros_method: SOD: commercially available kit; MDA: monitor the reaction of thiobarbituric acid at 535 nm
note: Mocked temperature using description in Methods Sec 2.2. Acclimation time = 1h. Control samples are also exposed to the increasing temp gradient. There is a CC (parallel control group) that are not exposed to the temp stress, but I don't have the data for it.  Control corals are collected at the same depth from patches not influenced by the thermal changes of the lagoon. Normal corals are those of normal appearance, and partially bleached corals show partial discoloration of branches. Depth <1m.

title: Visibly healthy corals exhibit variable pigment concentrations and symbiont phenotypes
site: Kaneohe Bay, Coconut Island, Hawaii, USA
trt_no: 2 species x 4 depths x 2 min and max - 1 group only has 1 colony = 16 - 1 = 15
note: Used temp from cluster. Same series for all depths. Colonies that displayed even green-brown pigmentation were identified as ‘healthy’ and sampled for the study. All corals were sampled between 9am and 1pm. Samples were taken from the top surface from the colony to ensure similar angles of incoming solar radiation and a homogenous surface area. Some samples contained visible endolithic algae at the base of the tissues. The chlorophyll b: chlorophyll a ratio of 0.79 was applied to estimate the chlorophyll a contribution from endolithic algae and subtracted from total chl a.

title: Exposure to solar radiation increases damage to both host tissues and algal symbionts of corals during thermal stress
site: Horseshoe Reef, Georgetown
trt_no: 1 temp x 3 light x 6 timepoints = 18
fvfm_name: Maximum quantum yield of chlorophyll fluorescence
note: RE = Recovery group. No temp data for this tank. corals immediately placed under full solar irradiances (2,100 quanta m2 s2) after collection. They bleached within 3–4 days. These corals were then placed in the flowing seawater table exposed to 550 lmole quanta m)2 s)1 PAR (same intensity as LL group). Fv/Fm was measured at 5 different times after heat stress has commenced (June 3). Temp data ended at June 8 730am. Text did not specify whoch day the Fv/Fm values are measured on, only specfied the hour. I used temp until June 7 of the specific hour for each observation.

trt_no: 3 species x 1 temp treatment x 2 tissue type x 9 timepoints = 54

title: A Connection between Colony Biomass and Death in Caribbean Reef-Building corals
site: Admiral Reef, Upper Florida Keys, USA
note: Depth 0-4m. At each site, six representative colonies of each species were tagged at the beginning of the study to ensure that subsequent collections were from the same coral colony. Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

note: Depth 0-4m. At each site, six representative colonies of each species were tagged at the beginning of the study to ensure that subsequent collections were from the same coral colony. Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

note: Depth 12-15m. At each site, six representative colonies of each species were tagged at the beginning of the study to ensure that subsequent collections were from the same coral colony. Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

note: Depth 0-4m. At each site, six representative colonies of each species were tagged at the beginning of the study to ensure that subsequent collections were from the same coral colony. Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

note: Depth 0-4m. At each site, six representative colonies of each species were tagged at the beginning of the study to ensure that subsequent collections were from the same coral colony. Due to the difficulty in permanently tagging the branches of A. cervicornis, this coral was sampled from up to six distinct colonies from the same population at every collection period, but not necessarily the same colonies each time. (Note: sample sizes of A. cervicornis at deeper sites were reduced [n = 2–3] due to its rarity at depth. Temperature from cluster. No temp data for second half of 1997 and the entire 1998. 96 out of 690 observations for this study habe no temp data. Palmata Beach and Norman's Pond have te same temperature data series. Used to last temp of the 30 days as observation temperature.

title: Reactive oxygen species (ROS) and dimethylated sulphur compounds in coral explants under acute thermal stress
site: Heron Island, Great Barrier Reef, Australia
trt_no: 2 temp = 2
fvfm_name: Dark-adapted maximum quantum yield of PSII
ros_type: Fluoresence of general ROS dye CM-H2DCFDA, DMSP, DMSO
ros_method: Incubated for 20 min in the dark using a 20 µmol l?1 final concentration of a general oxidative stress indicator, CM-H2DCFDA. 1:1 alkali cleavage of DMSP to DMS.
note: DMSP and DMSO were iN units of pmol um-3, but the values were so small for R so I converted them to amol um-3. coral explants: coral tissue was gently peeled from the coral skeleton, broken into smaller pieces and transferred into an autoclave dish. After 24h, viable explants were transferrred to fresh dishes. Cultured explants were maintained for 1 week (hence recovery = 7 days) until being transferred into beakers where the temperature is raised.

title: Thermal stress response in a dinoflagellate-bearing nudibranch and the octocoral on which it feeds
site: Casuarina Beach, New South Wales
trt_no: (2 temp x 2 tank + 1 control of control tank) x 21 timepoints x 3 species - (2 timepoints for 5 tanks for 1 species) - (2 timepoints for 1 tank for 1 species) = 315 - 10 -2 = 303
note: Depth NR. For each observation, there are 3-5 replicate measurements of Fv/Fm for each organism. All tanks were monitored 3 times daily for temp (800, 1400, 2000) until Jun6, then 2 times a day (800, 1400). Temperature tanks were monitored ~hourly from 800-2000 DURING the experimental period (May28-Jun2).

trt_no: (2 temp x 2 tank + 1 control of control tank) x 21 timepoints x 3 species - (2 timepoints for 5 tanks for 1 species) - (2 timepoints for 1 tank for 1 species) = 315 - 10 -2 = 303
note: Depth NR. For each observation, there are 3-5 replicate measurements of Fv/Fm for each organism. All tanks were monitored 3 times daily for temp (800, 1400, 2000) until Jun6, then 2 times a day (800, 1400). Temperature tanks were monitored ~hourly from 800-2000 DURING the experimental period (May28-Jun2).

trt_no: (2 temp x 2 tank + 1 control of control tank) x 21 timepoints x 3 species - (2 timepoints for 5 tanks for 1 species) - (2 timepoints for 1 tank for 1 species) = 315 - 10 -2 = 303
note: Depth NR. For each observation, there are 3-5 replicate measurements of Fv/Fm for each organism. All tanks were monitored 3 times daily for temp (800, 1400, 2000) until Jun6, then 2 times a day (800, 1400). Temperature tanks were monitored ~hourly from 800-2000 DURING the experimental period (May28-Jun2).

title: Bleaching and stress in coral reef ecosystems: hsp70 expression by the giant barrel sponge Xestospongia muta
site: Conch Reef and Conch Wall, Key Largo, Florida
exp_iv: Field/Lab, Bleaching, Sa, T, M, Depth
trt_no: Field: 2 bleaching x 2 tissues + 1 bleaching has 1 extra tissue = 5. Salinity: 4 Sa x 4 time = 16. Temp: 5 temp x 4 time = 20. Transplant: 4 depth conditions x 4 time = 16. 5+16+20+16 = 57
note: Used temp from cluster of June. Chl a content was standardized to sponge volume. Length, width, Height of sponge tissue was given. I calculated surface area and converted chl a to ug/cm2.

trt_no: Field: 2 bleaching x 2 tissues + 1 bleaching has 1 extra tissue = 5. Salinity: 4 Sa x 4 time = 16. Temp: 5 temp x 4 time = 20. Transplant: 4 depth conditions x 4 time = 16. 5+16+20+16 = 57
